\section{Introduction}

\begin{frame}[c]\frametitle{Introduction}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Gender wage gap is persistent and prevalent in the US.
       \item This paper shows turnover and human capital dynamics are important factors in explaining gender wage gap.
       \item They establish a structural model of wage dynamics, estimate it using NLSY79 data and do some counterfactual analysis.
        \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[c]\frametitle{Data}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item They use NLSY79 data and focus on period after the individuals' graduation.
       \item They exclude the individuals who never get employed after 15 years of graduation. Unemployment and out-of-the-labor force are both treated as non-employment state.
       \item They distinguish two group:high school graduates are those who have 12 to 15 years of schooling, college graduates are those who have 16 to 20 years of schooling.
       \item They restrict their sample to non-minority individuals who did not have any child while in school.
       \item They have 1,376 men and 1,331 women in the high school group, and 653 men and 681 women in the college group.
        \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[t]\frametitle{Gender wage gaps over the life-cycle}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item  $w_{i t}$ denotes the log hourly real wage of individual $i$ in week $t$, $M_{i t}$ denotes the number
        of months worker $i$ has spent in the labor force , and $\tau_y$ are calendar year
        fixed effects. 
         $ w_{i t}=\beta_0Male_i+\sum_{m=1}^{180}[\alpha_m \mathbb{1}[M_{i t}=m]+\beta_m(Male_i \mathbb{1}[M_{i t}=m])]+\tau_y+\varepsilon_{i t}$
        \end{itemize}  
